{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":85205,"duration_api_ms":132780,"num_turns":5,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"dcfa7f03-f6ac-4612-a5cd-a1c0a1828462","total_cost_usd":0.3591718,"usage":{"input_tokens":4,"cache_creation_input_tokens":23723,"cache_read_input_tokens":76363,"output_tokens":1806,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":23723,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":141,"outputTokens":6889,"cacheReadInputTokens":495818,"cacheCreationInputTokens":34707,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.12755154999999999,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":4,"outputTokens":1806,"cacheReadInputTokens":76363,"cacheCreationInputTokens":23723,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.23162025000000003,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"All three amendments identify verified, real defects in the codebase. Amendment fr-16-381b2bc1 addresses a concrete namespace collision between user-created milestone IDs and the internal .locks directory. Amendments fr-16-20005d1b and fr-16-20943f79 address complementary data integrity issues in the task run lineage system — one on the completion path (fallback to wrong row) and one on the start path (orphaned running rows). Code inspection confirms each claim.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-16-381b2bc1","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified: MilestoneId::new() rejects only '.' and '..' but allows other dot-prefixed names like '.locks'. MILESTONE_LOCKS_DIR is literally '.locks' and resolves to milestones/.locks/. A user creating milestone id '.locks' would collide with the lock directory used by all other milestones. Additionally, list_milestone_ids() skips dot-prefixed directories at enumeration time, so any dot-prefixed milestone would be invisible to listing while still existing on disk. Rejecting all dot-prefixed names at the MilestoneId::new() validation layer is the correct fix — it's a simple, durable invariant that closes both the collision and the invisible-milestone issues."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-20005d1b","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified: In update_task_run (fs.rs ~line 2928), when no exact run_id match is found, the code falls back to an open runless row. Meanwhile, record_bead_completion receives _started_at as a deliberately-unused parameter (underscore-prefixed, docstring confirms it's 'retained for compatibility' but ignored). Without started_at disambiguation, a completion bearing a new named run_id can silently attach to an older open attempt that has no run_id, corrupting the bead audit trail. The fix — failing fast when no exact run_id match exists — is correct and safe; same-attempt repair should happen through the start path where started_at is still available."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-20943f79","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified: The superseding block at fs.rs ~line 2827 is gated on `run_id.is_none()`, so when a new start with an explicit run_id arrives, the old runless running row is never superseded and remains permanently in Running state. find_runs_for_bead will then return contradictory history — one attempt still 'running' alongside a later retry that already succeeded. The same_attempt() function in model.rs only matches runless entries by started_at timestamp, so these orphaned rows won't be collapsed away. This is a real data integrity defect. Either superseding the stale legacy row at start time or rejecting the new start until the old row is resolved would fix it."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"63d44e63-e636-4634-8fc5-5c97de8f06bb"}
